ce:section.ce:para:
The surface functional states and elemental compositions of the Z-CDs were determined by XPS survey data (Fig. 2
                        ). The presence of carbon, oxygen, and Zn within the nanomaterial structure was indicated by the characteristic peaks observed at binding energy levels of 288, 534, 1020, and 1044 eV, respectively (Fig. 2A). From the deconvoluted C1s spectrum (Fig. 2B), five peaks at 282.6 eV, 286.8 eV, 287.5 eV, 288.1, and 291.6 eV which are associated with sp2 C, C–C/CC, CO, C–O, and COOH functional groups, respectively. Moreover, the O1s core-level spectrum split into peaks with binding energies at 530.3 eV, 534 eV, and 534.5 eV that belong to the CO/Zn–O, C–O, and C–OH/C–O–C groups, respectively (Fig. 2C) (Tammina, Yang, Li, Koppala, & Yang, 2019). Also, the high-resolution spectrum of Zn 2p (Fig. 2D) illustrates three peaks at 1020 eV and 1044 eV with an energy gap of 22 eV, which can be ascribed to the Zn 2p core levels with the splitting of Zn 2p3/2 and Zn 2p1/2, respectively. In addition, the powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) pattern of the as-synthesized Z-CDs is presented in Fig. 3
                        A, which shows a broad peak at ∼22.1° related to the planes of the graphite carbon material, and the characteristic diffraction peaks at 2θ:30.1°, 32.9°, 41.7°, and 43.3° are in accordance with the Joint Committee Powder Diffraction Standard (JCPDS) data, No. 00-021-1486, which confirms the presence Zn dopant in the CDs (Khare, Bhati, Anand, Gunture, & Sonkar, 2018).
